<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO ARTHUR ET AL.</font><br>
<tt>Sun Apr 20 14:47:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Arthur,<br>
    You're not the only one who had a bit of emotional burnout.  Between the 2 week round robin for Marc &amp; Co, a lead role in a &quot;Poetry-Ritual-Theater&quot; performance, and several local and state veterans' activities, I needed recharge time for a few weeks, and then couldn't get back on the net with the rest of the family putting in major hours.<br><br>
Kali, by the way, is the Hindu goddess of death. Many movies, &quot;Around the World in 80 Days&quot; for example, have used the old &quot;rescue the hostage from the murderous worshippers of Kali&quot; plot.  She's usually depicted with 6 arms, I think, each wielding a sword. Definately a fun deity. Would make a good consort for Mars. <br><br>
The problem, as I see it, with people like Kali, is that it makes a much simpler unambiguous world without messy complexities if one can divide everything into &quot;pure good&quot; and &quot;pure evil&quot;, and then attribute all actions to one of these two motives. Never mind that much if not most of the wrongs and errors committed in this world from day to day are influnenced by mixed motives and stem from varying degrees of incompetence or ignorance. And I include myself in there with everyone else. I believe we're all far from perfect. The question is whether we are open to growth and seriously try to become what we were created to be. Partcipating in a war very often has a negative effect here. 
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot; 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


